[normal]ii)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Legality of the residence test
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Disproportionately affect migrants and children
[normal], and will
[normal] therefore indirectly discriminate against those with a particular race, age, ethnicity or nationality. This has implications pursuant to th
[normal]e Equality Act 2010 and Article 14 ECHR (when considered alongside Article 6 ECHR).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Directly discriminate against all children who do not meet the proposed test, including (
[normal]i
[normal]) British children under the age of 12 months who are unable to prove their citiz
[normal]enship entitlement, (ii) migrant children who have been lawfully resident in the UK for less than 12 months and (iii) migrant children unlawfully resident in the UK who as minors without legal capacity or financial resources, cannot be held culpable for fa
[normal]iling to seek to 
[normal]regularise
[normal] their status or seek privately- paid legal advice. It is no answer that local authorities can foot the financial bill, as in many cases such vulnerable and undocumented children will not be known to social services and even if t
[normal]hey are, social workers are not immigration law experts and often do not 
[normal]recognise
[normal] the advice needs of migrant children and young people. Local authority in- house teams are prohibited from providing immigration law advice, as advisors are not OISC registe
[normal]red.
[normal] There would also be serious questions regarding conflicts of interest and competing instructions if in-house local authority teams were to take on such work. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]D
[normal]irectly and/ or indirectly discriminate against EEA nationals and their family members, ma
[normal]ny of whom derive lawful rights of residence through the interpretation of EU law by domestic and international courts, in circumstances where not all rights have been comprehensively incorporated into domestic law.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]i
[normal]ii
[normal])
[normal]              
[normal]The residence test- not fit for pu
[normal]rpose
