[normal]Abdul is a 17 year old Bangladeshi national whose mother has a history of mental health issues. He was in care from the age of 10 to 13 and then went 
[normal]to live with his father until a year and half ago when he returned to his mother. Abdul’s mother assaulted and threatened Abdul with a knife and the police said it was not safe for him to return home. Abdul approached the Local Authority for assistance and
[normal] was advised that he should sofa-surf until he went to university. With specialist support we challenged the local authority’s refusal to carry out a child in need assessment and provide Abdul with accommodation by way of a pre-action protocol letter. Abdu
[normal]l was then provided with support and accommodation from Social Services. This sort of action against a public body whom is meant to have the best interests of a young person in mind, would not be possible without the help of free and independent specialist
[normal] lawyers.
