[normal]Sarah is a 17 year old who was refer
[normal]red for psychiatric services when she was rescued by a passer-by from attempting to throw herself off a bridge. Sarah is the sole 
[normal]carer
[normal] for her mother and younger siblings and has been finding it difficult to cope with her studies and responsibilities. Sar
[normal]ah’s mother refuses to engage with support services and Sarah’s psychiatrist has been trying to refer Sarah to the local authority for a child in need assessment under the Children Act 1989 but was not having any success in doing so. Sarah’s mother told he
[normal]r that she could not return to the house and Sarah was facing street homelessness. 
[normal]Streetlegal
[normal] wrote a pre-action protocol letter challenging the local authority’s failure to carried out the assessment and provide Section 20 accommodation. Following this t
[normal]he local authority accommodated Sarah whilst an assessment was being carried out by social services. The local authority then accepted a full Section 20 duty under the Children Act 1989 to accommodate and look after Sarah. Sarah would have been unable to v
[normal]entilate her case without the expert help of legal aid lawyers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Amber is a 20 year old who has two children aged 1 and 2. Amber’s mother was diagnosed with cancer in January 2010 when she was pregnant with her second child. Amber’s mother asked her to lea
[normal]ve as there was not enough space in the house for her to stay. Amber approached the local authority to make a housing application and was told that she could only apply for private rented accommodation and was not entitled to temporary accommodation. The L
[normal]ocal Authority however did not offer any private accommodation and each time Amber called up she was told someone would call back but they never did. Amber’s mother passed away in November 2010 and has still not been provided with any accommodation. Amber’
[normal]s mother left her housing association to Amber’s older brother with whom Amber has always had a difficult relationship. Amber’s brother was 
[normal]pressurising
[normal] her to leave and additionally there was an insect infestation in the house that he was refusing to addr
[normal]ess. Amber’s doctor wrote a letter concerning Amber’s skin condition and the local authority had still not provided her with any accommodation. 
[normal]Streetlegal
[normal] wrote a letter to the local authority proposing to commence judicial review proceedings if they did 
[normal]not provide Amber with emergency temporary accommodation. Amber and her children were then provided with suitable accommodation. Amber was a particularly vulnerable young person who would have had little prospect of rectifying her situation without the ass
[normal]istance of a legal aid lawyer.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Mark was accommodated by the Local Authority under a Part VII homeless application under the Housing Act 1996 at 17 years old. When M turned 18 a Section 184 decision was made that he was not in priority need for accommodati
[normal]on. Mark was receiving psychiatric treatment and had been diagnosed with borderline personality disorder and had attempted suicide on two occasions while in temporary accommodation. When Mark received the letter saying he had been found not to be in priori
[normal]ty need for accommodation and 
[normal]cancelling his housing he attempted suicide and was 
[normal]hospitalised
[normal]. 
[normal]Streetlegal
[normal] obtained a psychiatric report confirming that he would be vulnerable if he were street homeless as a result of his mental health issues and relied o
[normal]n 
[normal]caselaw
[normal] that it was unlawful for the Local Authority to have delayed the decision on his housing case until he turned 18. 
[normal]Streetlegal
[normal] then requested a Section 202 review and made representations for interim accommodation with a threat of Judicial review 
[normal]if the Local Authority did not provide it. The local authority provided interim accommodation and withdrew their Section 184 decision following full representation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Tom was in his late 30’s when he approached ILC in a highly distressed state. He explained he was homeless having fled his secure accommodation due to homophobic violence. Tom was a former care leaver and had been subjected to severe sexual and e
[normal]motional abuse during his time in care. Tom had been sectioned in the past and had a history of trying to take his own life. He applied to the local authority as a homeless person and was told verbally he was not vulnerable and temporary accommodation was 
[normal]denied. In desperation he tried to commit suicide and was 
[normal]hospitalised
[normal]. Upon his release from hospital Tom again approached the local authority homelessness department and 
[normal]he was told that he was 
[normal]not vulnerable and therefore not in priority need. By the ti
[normal]me he reached ILC it was mid-afternoon and he was very distressed and informed us that he felt like killing himself. Urgent contact was made with the local authority and a request for urgent interim accommodation was made. Psychiatric evidence was provided
[normal] to the authority together with a request for the authority to review its decision under section 202 of the Housing Act 1996 (Part VII). The authority declined to provide interim accommodation pending the outcome of the review request. ILC had no option bu
[normal]t to issue judicial review proceedings and seek urgent injunctive relief. That evening the High Court ordered the authority to provide interim accommodation. Whilst proceedings were issued the matter did not go to permission or a full trial as the local au
[normal]thority conceded their position, and Tom was spared the stress and trauma of lengthy litigation in the High Court. Tom was clearly very vulnerable and had the local authority fulfilled its statutory duty and made enquiries into his circumstances whilst pla
[normal]cing him in temporary accommodation, a judicial review would have been avoided.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Shareen
[normal] is a 19 year old victim of sexual violence and was trafficked into 
[normal]the UK for the purposes of sexual exploitation. She was supported by a trafficking charity who helped her make a claim for asylum. She is extremely traumatized and an urgent referral to a qualified psychiatrist has been made. There is a wealth of evidence 
[normal]confirming her highly distressed state and concerns over her fitness for interview. Written submissions are made to the Home Office to request that her 
[normal]asylum 
[normal]interview be delayed pending the assessment of the psychiatrist. The Home Office refuse to postpo
[normal]ne the interview. Professionals are extremely concerned that compelling 
[normal]Shareen
[normal] to attend an interview may damage her mental health and 
[normal]there is a risk that such an interview may 
[normal]retrigger trauma. We write to the Home Office to advise that we will have no 
[normal]choice but to lodge a claim for judicial review if they fail to reschedule the interview. If 
[normal]Shareen
[normal] does not attend her 
[normal]interview, 
[normal]and the Home Office do not agree to rescheduling
[normal],
[normal] her claim for asylum can be refused on non-compliance grounds.
[normal] 
[normal]The Home Of
[normal]fice refuse to engage with numerous pre-action correspondence and we have no choice but to lodge a claim 
[normal]including
[normal] an urgent application for interim relief from the court. The judge considering the application orders that the interview be postponed pending
[normal] the outcome of the psychiatric assessment. Subsequently, we are contacted by Treasury Solicitors. We receive an apology for the lack of correspondence and advised that the decision to refuse our requests were made by a ‘new member of staff’ and the pre-ac
[normal]tion correspondence had not reached a senior official in time. The case is conceded and there is no need for the case to go up to a judge to consider whether permission be granted.
