[normal]M
[normal]ohammed
[normal] is a 
[normal]16 year old
[normal] who was in the care of a Local Authority. He was abused and exploited as a street child in Libya and later in Greece, having arrived into the UK to seek safety. Due to his past traumatic experiences he be
[normal]came depressed, addicted to solvents and later heroin. As a result, he was convicted for petty offences. During his time in Young Offenders Institute (YOI) he was not provided adequate support services or access to 
[normal]behaviour
[normal] management courses
[normal]. He was 
[normal]plac
[normal]ed in segregation for lengthy periods of time all of which had a direct impact on his rehabilitation. He was also denied access to contact with his mother. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A
[normal]dam
[normal] is a 17 year old 
[normal]national from Senegal
[normal] with 
[normal]severe 
[normal]mental health problems. He has indefinite 
[normal]leave to remain in the UK and his family are British Citizens. He was charged and sentenced for offences relating to his gang affiliation in a local 
[normal]housing estate in North London.  
[normal]Unfortunately, there has been a breakdown in the family relationship and t
[normal]he Home Office have decided to take deport action to remove him from the UK. 
[normal]Upon release he was denied support from the Local Authority. He was later assessed as having significant cognitive impairments with an assessed mental capacity of a 5 year old. Sp
[normal]ecialist legal advice was needed to ensure that the Local Authority fulfilled their statutory duties to provide adequate accommodation, support services and protection from gang reprisals.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Belinda is 16 year old from the DRC. Her family were killed duri
[normal]ng the civil conflict whereby significant human rights abuses were committed against women and children. Belinda is orphaned at the age of 12 and has been raped on numerous occasions. She is later trafficked for the purposes of sexual exploitation through 
[normal]several African countries. 
[normal]During this time she falls pregnant and is subjected to a forced abortion. 
[normal]Her traffickers 
[normal]later 
[normal]facilitate her entry to the UK through a false visa placing her age beyond her actual minority. She is internally trafficked through
[normal] England and is imprisoned in a brothel for several years. Belinda was finally able to escape her trafficking situation and was street homeless in a major UK city before she was helped by a female stranger. When she arrived at the police station she was pl
[normal]aced into the care of the Local Authority and housed in a foster placement because of her vulnerabilities. 
[normal]She is taken to the Home Office by her social worker. At no stage have the police or the Local Authority disputed Belinda’s minority, she was 16 at t
[normal]he time. Having arrived at the Home Office the immigration official note that she is trafficked victim having listened to Belinda’s account and that of her social worker. Whilst at the Home Office Belinda is abandoned by her social worker. She has no idea 
[normal]where she has gone and is forced to wait at the Home Office alone before she is told to travel with a man and boy in a car. Belinda does not know where she is being taken and is extremely scared. Upon leaving the car she is met by a housing officer who inf
[normal]orms her that she will be staying at the accommodation before she is taken back to the Home Office. A week later Belinda is taken to the Home Office and told that her age is being disputed. The Home Office rely on the visa application that was used to faci
[normal]litate her entry to the UK. She is taken to adult accommodation for asylum seekers. She is alone and isolated for several weeks before the accommodation she lives in is raided by immigration officers. She is arrested and taken to HMP Holloway having been c
[normal]harged with immigration offences for making a false claim for asylum and entering the UK unlawfully. Whilst in prison concerns about her mental health and minority are raised by prison staff and immigration officers but no steps are taken to assess her nee
[normal]ds and provide her with appropriate support. Once the case was referred to use we secured he release from prison, she was age assessed by a Local Authority who later found her to be a child and she was placed in a foster placement once again. 
